<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Global Campaign for Education (GCE) UK submission to IDSC inquiry on Disability and Development</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Global Campaign for Education (GCE) UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ubmission to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">IDSC inquiry on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Development</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We welcome DFID’s recent commitments on disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which are an important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to developing country partners and other donors. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The UK is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the leading donor for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commitments could help to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">galvanise international action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to include disabled children and young people in education.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disabled people are among the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">most marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from education but also from other services, and f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ace </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">daily</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discrimination.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> a high level, cross-cutting strategy on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">championed at a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">senior</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> level and sensibly phased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> towards the equitable inclusion of disabled people in all UK aid programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, change will only happen with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rigorous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID should move towards making the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inclusion of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a requirement of bilateral and multilateral funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ith all education programmes a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">priority.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">isability-inclusive approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">will not become reality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">without </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">full implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> by DFID’s Country Offices </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and in-country partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Top-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level strategy must be complemented by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">embedding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">-inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> into core processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with strong </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">accountability mechanisms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ensure delivery a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">country level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, training and support for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">country advisers,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of all programmes by disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alongside gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, age</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">factors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘mainstream</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’ disability into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> education programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, with an emphasis throu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ghout on inclusive education that benefits all children, especially the most marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ll teacher-training supported by DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> incorporate inclusive teaching methodology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This should be supported by the necessary resources, specific timeframes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for implementation, and clear accountability. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll programmes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to show h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ow they reach disabled children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young people and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In line with a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘twin track’ approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, DFID should put in place </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">additional resources and support to re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ach disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should develop a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled Children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Education Challenge Fund’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> using the learning from the Girls’ Education Challenge Fund, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">invest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to strengthen the evidence base on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability must be a core priority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for post-2015 as part of a wider focus on equity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> continue to champion the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">leave no one behind’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> principle, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of all targets by disability, and the principle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that disabled people have to be included in order for target</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e considered achieved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A goal of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">quality education for all, prioritising the most marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is urgent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly needed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to address</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the crisis in educational equity and quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership on Disability Data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ to improve t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he data and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About GCE UK</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Global Campaign for Education is an international education campaign, with over 80 national coalitions across all continents. GCE UK is the UK branch of this campaign: we are a coalition of 30 international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development NGOs and education unions</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. GCE UK maintains a strong link with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parliament, working closely with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">APPG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on Global Education for All, and through the ‘Sen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d My Friend to School’ campaign</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">isability, education, exclusion and poverty</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ty must be recognised as a core development issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">80% of disabled people live in developing countries and the UN calls them “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">the world’s largest minority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It is clear that the MDGs, and post-2015 goals, will not be achieved without the inclusion of dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">abled people. Ensuring that disabled people are included </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aid programmes is an obligation under the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The MDG of achieving universal primary education by 2015 is “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">not on track</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with 57 millio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n children of primary age still out of school and progress all but stalled. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">250 million children are in school but failing to learn</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Global Campaign for Education argues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that in most countries, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disabled children are more likely to be out of school tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n any other group of children</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Nepal, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an estimated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">85% of all children out of sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hool are disabled. In Ethiopia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, fewer than 3% of disabled children have access to primary education</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A study by Plan International of its 1.4 million sponsored children recently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concluded that the likelihood that a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">child did not attend school was often more than ten times greater than a child without a disability</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disabled children are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> likely to remain in school and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> move</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> up to the next year group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many statistics quoted ab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">out disability are contestable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">because </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the invisibility of disabled people from national statistics in developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The data gap has a major impact on ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ucation, where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">even basic data on disabled children in and out of school is frequently absent</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Planning for the inclusion of disabled children is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenging without information about the type of impairment children have (whether long term physical, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ental, intellectual or sensory impairment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability is highly interrelated to other aspects of inequality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he exclusion of certain populations including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">people but also girls and women, ethnic, religious and linguistic minorities, and those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> living in remote rural areas or informal settlements has hindered progress towards the MDGs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">fferent dimensions of exclusion overlap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adolescent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnic minority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> living with disabilities experience triple exclusion. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f all the excluding factors, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability has the strongest correlation with poor educational outcomes</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">approach to disability</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We welcome DFID’s recent commitments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that all schools built with direct DFID support will be accessible, an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d the commitment to work with partners to improve data and evidence on disability</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">announcements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">an important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">statement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to othe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">r donors and developing countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the UK is serious about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> its aid programmes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s worked hard to support DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to strengthen its focus on disabled children’s education, and we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">urge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to build on this progress </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to become a world </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">leader on disability, in particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">by committing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">teacher-training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> supported by DFID will incorpo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> inclusive teaching methodology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strong momentum, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">examples of good practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no formal framework for the systematic inclusion of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> throughout its programmes, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no formal checks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are in place to ensure that disabled p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eople benefit from UK Aid.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> previously recognised the importance of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">“twin-track” approach to disability</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which sees the active “mainstreaming” or inclusion of disabled people in all aspects of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ment work (eg.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensuring education programmes support disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), coupled with additional inputs and resources which recognise the marginalisation of disabled people and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides them with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> target</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed support.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">This approach should now be thoroughly emb</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">edded in DFID’s work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID has previously</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> taken steps to integrate disability within its education programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. GCE UK welcomed DFID’s production in 2010 of a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Guidance Note on Education for Children with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and later worked with DFID to produc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e a summary ‘one-pager’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which was sent by DFID to all Country Offices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK survey of six countries</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suggested that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">only half </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of these Country Offices were aware of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the ‘one-pager’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, and only one was implementing it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In its report ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Equity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and Inclusion for All in Education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">analysed 14 DFID Country Operational Plans and found </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">just two mentions of disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raised concern that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, although there were examples of good practice,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">little evidence of DFID engaging in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategic planning to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> education initiatives prioritised marginalised groups – such as disabled children - in a comprehensive way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">could draw many lessons from its success in mainstreaming gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and prioritising girls and women, and co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld apply these to disability. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Towards a strategic approach to disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">-inclusion</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arriers to education for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are the result of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complex factors involving social, economic and political systems, and the way in which schools engage with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Responding to these barriers requires strategic cross-sector planning. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">therefore develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> a high level, cross-cutting strategy on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, and implement this in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sensible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">phased </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">approach at all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">levels of its work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This strategy could draw lessons from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s Strategic Vision for Girls and Women</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and the disability strategy of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Australia’s development agency</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The strategy should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">championed at a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">senior</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, clearly emphasising its importance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">internally and to partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a paper strategy will not lead to sustainable change without</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rigorous</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID should move towards making the inclusion of disabled people a requirement of bilateral and multilateral funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> programmes a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> priority.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK’s analysis highlights that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">devolved nature of DFID’s operations creates challenges for consistent implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trategy must be complemented by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">embedding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability responsiveness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> into core processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with strong </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">acco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">untability mechanisms to ensure delivery at the country level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">training and support for country advisers,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation of all programmes by disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The inclusion of disabled people should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a requirement of all DFID Business Cases and Country Op</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">erational Plans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A network of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">trained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">leads/focal points in all DFID Country Offices </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should report back regularly to a central senior </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Champion’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on planning, implementation and evaluation of inclusive programmes. These leads could also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">contact points for consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with external groups of (and groups representing) disabled people. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However lessons should be learned from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of gender mainstreaming. DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">previously </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highlighted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that gender focal points often proved disappoi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nting due to a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">"...lack of clarity about their roles and responsibilities [and] lack of management support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">"</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another risk is that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">staff may assume that since the focal point is ‘doing disability’ no-one else has to do anything. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Focal points therefore need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to be given sufficient resources, time and authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK welcomes DFID’s existing support for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled People’s Organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DPOs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> play </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an important role,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empower</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabled people to participate in decisions that affect them, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> attitudes towards disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in society at large. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">continue to strengthen its support for DPOs, using a range of approaches that deliver effective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">participation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">place a clear requirement on its Country Offices to in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">volve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DPOs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in programme development, implementation and evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Implementing education for disabled children: What works</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK is strongly supportive of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s leading position as the largest bilateral donor to basic education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We urge DFID to use t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his position to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">further prioritise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">-inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">galvanise other donors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and see a step-change in support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to disabled children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nequal access to education is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exacerbated by the prevalence o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f a medical deficit model of disability, which perpetuates the notion that disabled children must adapt in order to ‘integrate’ into mainstream schooling, or be educated in a separate ‘special’ education system</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. At the same time, the nature of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impairments is often poorly understood, resulting in inappropriate service provision. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE UK argues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">carefully planned and implemented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inclusive education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> utilising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the expertise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> staff in rehabilitation services and special education schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that support the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inclusion of disabled children in mainstream schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are appropriate in the large maj</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ority of cases. Such strategies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enhance the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">quality of teaching and learning for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">all chil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">dren</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, not just disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">embed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> inclusive education as a leading principle of its education programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, thereby strengthening the focus on disabled children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simultaneously</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> strengthening education systems and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">quality of learning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for all children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s commitment on accessible school construction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is welcome, it is important to note that directly-funded school construction forms only a small part of DFID’s work. Similar commitments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should be made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in areas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">which constitute a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> greater part of DFID’s spending and portfolio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensuring that provisions are made for accessible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">school infrastructure, transport and learning materials</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID is a stro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng leader i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n supporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">teacher training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which is fundamental to meeting MDG 2 and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improving the quality of education</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In order to be inclusive of disabled children, teachers need to learn about and practise inclusive education during pre-service and in-service training</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should integrate inclusive education throughout the teacher-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">training it supports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, and seek to also train specialised teaching assistants to support children with complex needs within a mainstream environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">promote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the recruitment of disabled teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> including the reasonable adjustments needed in sch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ools for this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">play</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an influencing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> role in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">developing country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">overnments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability-inclusion in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the education system and governance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ne systemic barrier is the problem of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">divided ministerial responsibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where education for disabled children is the responsibility of a different ministry than that responsible for the education of non-disabled children</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This division usually reflects the view that the disabled need welfare rather than equity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in educational </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opportunity and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often leads to segregated responses to disability. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The marginalisation of those with disabilities is often compounded by other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inequalities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For instance, girls with disabilities are less likely to get an education, vocational training or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> employment than boys with disabilities or girls without disabilities</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID should build on its strong work to reach marginalised girls – such as the Girls Education Challenge Fund</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> ensur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> that such mechanisms support disabled girls</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here are good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> examples of GEC projects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to do this</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and we urge DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make this systematic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">establishing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> support for disabled girls </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a requirement of all GEC projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In line with the “twin-track” approach, DFID should put in place </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">additional resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to support disabled children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’s education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Establish</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled Children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Education Challenge Fund’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> based on the learning from the Girls’ Education Challenge Fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">evidence base on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">successful interventions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that enhance learning for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled students</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Any research should ensure the participation of disabled people and DPOs, and qualitative research should complement quantitative research to ensure disabled people’s perspect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ves are he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ard.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fund i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nnovative community-based and school-based projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to reach disabled children and young people and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improve their access to basic services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Eg.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Holistic p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rojects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">addressing social, economic, cul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tural, physical, communication and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">barriers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rojects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> relating to the awareness, education and understanding of all those involved in school management, including strengthening </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled people's participation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; or C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommunity outreach work supporting children and young people with complex need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rojects to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">build the capacity of education systems, schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to deliver </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inclusive, gender-equitable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Use its influence to e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nhanc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in-country coordination and collaboration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to address disabled children’s learning needs. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Education for disabled children is a good investment</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highlights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">educating children with disabilities is a good investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Prioritising disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within DFID’s work should not be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thought of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in terms of an additional cost burden. O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n the contrary, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the costs of not investing in support to disabled people are much greater to the countries where DFID is seeking to deliver development progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. By one estimate, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">USD 135–192 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">billion is lost from the GDP of low-income countries per annum as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a result of disabled people’s exclusion from the labour market</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ducating disabled children reduces welf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are costs and future dependence, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increases children’s own potential productivity and wealth creation in turn help</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to alleviate poverty</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n ma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ny cases, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">where disabled people and their needs are considered early in the planning of projects, additional costs are minimal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Directly relevant to DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commitment on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">school construction, UNICEF note that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the costs of integrating accessibility into new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">buildings can be negligible (less than 1% of the total cost) compared to the higher cost of making adaptations to completed buildings.</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Working with partners globally</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID should invest in projects to improve disability statistics </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to better measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For instance, working closely with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Washington Group on Disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y Statistics and with UNICEF, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providing financial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and technical assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to national statistical agencies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is also important to invest in partici</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">patory qualitative research looking at the impact of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nclusive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rojects being rolled out, such as looking at “Quality of Life” measures, in order to establish best practice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should lead in working with other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partners to improve support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for disabled children. This includes other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">donors such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AusAid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and multil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aterals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">like the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership for Education (GPE), UNESCO and the World Bank</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is represented on the Board of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the GPE, whose </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new strategic plan includes a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tegic focus on ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Reaching Every Child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with inclusive education a priority within its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation plan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The GPE is the only multilateral partnership devoted to getting all children into school for a quality education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and with the GPE’s replenishment t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aking place in 2014 the UK has an important opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strengthen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> GPE’s focus on disabled children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Post-2015: a turning point for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Prime Minister and DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> already shown </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> leade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rship on the need for post-2015 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oals to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">include disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. GCE UK welcomed the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">High Level Panel’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (HLP)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recommendations as they relate to disability, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the "</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">no one left behind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">" transformative shift; the emphasis on the need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation of indicators by disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for meas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uring progress; and the commitment that "</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">no target should be considered met unless met for all social groups, including people with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">"</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We urge DFID to champion these elements as the negotiations continue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nsuring disabled children and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">marginalised groups are both in school and learning is a critical challenge for post-2015</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HLP’s illustrative goal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Provide q</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">uality education and lifelong learning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” rightly emphasises that there is an education crisis with millions denied their right </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to education.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">urge DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to fight for an education goal and targets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for universal, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">free, quality early childhood, primary and secondary education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tackle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> inequalities and guarantee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> education rights for all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. Progress </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, completi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">on and learning outcomes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregated by disability alongside gender, wealth, age, location and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">factors.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n order to better measure progress there needs to be a “data revolution” and nowhere is that more true than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GCE UK urges </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to play a leading role in a multi-stakeholder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership on Disability Data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to improve the visibility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and focus on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> GCE UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">member organisations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">listed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> at </span><a href="http://groupspaces.com/GCEUK/pages/members"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://groupspaces.com/GCEUK/pages/members</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.sendmyfriend.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.sendmyfriend.org/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> UN Enable (2013), ‘Factsheet on Persons with Disabilities’, </span><a href="http://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?id=18"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?id=18</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> See: </span><a href="http://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?navid=14&amp;pid=150"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">h</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">ttp://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?navid=14&amp;pid=150</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a hre